SYMPTOM_TEXT: After receiving the vaccine, my arm was sore, but no more than expected - it was like getting the flu vaccine. A week later, I noticed I had a hive around the injection site. It was about 2x3 inches, sore, hot, and bumpy. It stayed that way for about two days, then got super itchy and remained tender and hot. About day five, the hive part became more of a ring and started to expand. I'm now a week in and the hive ring has expanded to about half of my upper arm. The itching has started to subside. It's still warm to the touch, but not hot. The reaction may have been exacerbated by another issue - several years ago I had the shoulder on the same side as the injection replaced and had an allergic reaction to the dermabond used to seal the surgical incision and to the pain meds. I'm also allergic to the metal used in the replacement. The scar reacts by getting red, hot, puffy, and itchy whenever my allergies are bothering me. The injection reaction area included the incision and it's been a major part of the issue. While this may have contributed to the strength of the reaction, the "hive circle" has expanded in all directions - not just over the scar.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: When patient came in for her second dose of Moderna vaccine at 28 weeks, she reported a reaction that occurred about 10 to 12 day after the first dose at the site where her injection was given. She brought pictures on her cell phone of a large of erythema and raised hard bumps that covered most of her upper outer arm. The area was approximately 9cm top to bottom x 7cm wide. It first felt itchy, then broke out in this dense red rash. She was seen by her primary physician who told her it looked like an allergic medicine reaction and he advise against taking a second dose. She came in to see what we advised her to do. We advised her to follow her physician's recommendations and withheld the second dose of Moderna.

No adverse reactions were reported. The Vaccine was given posterior to ideal vaccine administration site. When given posterior to center of mass of deltoid, there is a question on whether the vaccine was given in subcutaneous tissue or in muscle. When we learned of this, we did a qualitative IgG test , and IgG was present. This leads us to the conclusion that it was given intramuscularly and an immune response has been mounted. We also called Moderna for advice and their response was to NOT repeat the dose and to continue with the second dose as normal. We gave the second dose intramuscularly 28 days later as planned.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Other related health complications; Shingles; could not sleep; This spontaneous report was received from a 69 year old male patient with cholesterol abnormal, diabetes and no known drug reactions or allergies refers to himself. The patient's medical history included chicken pox as a boy. Concomitant medication included unspecified cholesterol and diabetes medication. In approximately July 2013 (reported as 2 to 3 months ago), the patient was vaccinated with a dose of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) to prevent shingles (dose, dose number, route, anatomical site of vaccination, lot # and expiration date were not provide). On approximately 03-OCT-2013 (reported as about a week ago), the patient had shingles. It started with soreness on the right side of his abdomen, then a rash that spread to the navel area. He had sharp pain internally and externally and could not sleep for 4 days. Currently the pain was gone but he still had some rash and soreness. The patient sought medical attention by doctor visit. As treatment he received calamine lotion and unspecified psychotropic. Blood work was performed but the result was unknown. At the time of the report, the outcome of events was reported as recovering. The causal assessment between the events and zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) was not reported.  Follow up information was received on 02-MAR-2021 from a lawyer regarding a case in litigation and refers to 69-year-old male patient. No information was provided regarding concomitant medications, concurrent conditions or medical history. On 10-JUN-2013, the patient was inoculated with zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) (also reported as shingles vaccine) prophylaxis (dose, dose number, route, anatomical site of vaccination, lot # and expiration date were not provided) at a pharmacy (he was 69-year-old when he received the vaccine). On 02-OCT-2013, as a result of his receipt of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), he suffered shingles, including any and all of its sequelae. On an unknown date, he also experienced other related health conditions (ill-defined disorder). As a result of his receipt of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient had been caused to suffer severe personal injuries, pain, suffering, and emotional distress, as well as to incur substantial economic damages and loss of consortium damages. As a result of the foregoing acts and omissions, the patient was caused to suffer serious and dangerous side effects including shingles, as well as other severe and personal injuries which were permanent and lasting in nature, physical pain and mental anguish, including diminished enjoyment of life, as well as the need for lifelong medical treatment, monitoring and/or medications. As a result of the foregoing acts and omissions the patient also required and/or would require more health care and services and did incur medical, health, incidental and related expenses. In addition, the patient required and would continue to require healthcare and services. He had incurred and would continue to incur medical and related expenses. Besides, he had suffered and would continue to suffer diminished capacity for the enjoyment of life, a diminished quality of life, increased risk of premature death, aggravation of preexisting conditions, activation of latent conditions, and other losses and damages. The patient reported direct medical losses and costs included physician care, monitoring, and treatment. He had incurred and would continue to incur mental and physical pain and suffering. The outcome of herpes zoster and ill-defined disorder was reported as not recovered. The causal relationship between the events and zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) was assessed as related. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Blood pressure was 180/101; numbness on whole left side of body; tingling; A spontaneous report was received from a consumer concerning a 68 years-old, female patient who received Modern's COVID-19 vaccine (mRNA-1273) and  hospitalized for blood pressure that was 180/101 and experienced numbness on whole left side of body, and tingling.  The patient's medical history included hypertension, allergies to penicillin, IV contrast (highly allergic, has to be pre-medicated if uses it 2-3 days before), and sulfa, and unspecified issues with sodium. Concomitant product use included blood pressure medication.    On 24 Feb 2021 at 09:45 am, prior to the onset of the events, the patient received the first dose of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 (lot/batch: unknown) intramuscularly in the left arm for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection.   On 24 Feb 2021, approximately 2 hours after receiving the dose at 11:00 am, the patient's left side started going numb. The patient went home at 02:30 pm and took some Motrin, but still had numbness and tingling. At around 07:00 pm same day, the patient reported blood pressure was 180/101 beats per minute. Patient reported taking prescribed blood pressure medicine prior to getting the vaccine on 24 Feb 2021 and Motrin after the vaccination on 24 Feb 2021 in order to stop the numbness.   In the morning of 25 Feb 2021, patient's blood pressure was very high until 04:00 am; therefore, patient went to the emergency room (ER).  At the hospital, they were very concerned about patient's blood pressure because it remained high. The patient thought the numbness and tingling would stop but they didn't. Patient denied numbness in arms; but felt it in legs and all up left side. Due to prior "issues with sodium", patient had to be treated for sodium levels at the hospital. Patient was discharged out of the hospital on 26 Feb 2021. All tests came back normal. Numbness on side and tingling went away. The patient believed reaction was due to the vaccine even though it was temporary.   Treatment information included Motrin.   Action taken with mRNA-1273 in response to the events is not reported.   The events blood pressure was 180/101, numbness on whole left side of body, and tingling were considered resolved.; Reporter's Comments: Based on the current available information and temporal association between the use of the product and the start date of the events approximately 2 hours after receiving the dose, a causal relationship cannot be excluded. However, patient's hx of hypertension, allergies to penicillin, IV contrast and sulfa, and issues with sodium are confounding factors that may play a possible contributory role providing an alternative explanation.
LAB_DATA: Test Date: 20210224; Test Name: Blood pressure; Result Unstructured Data: High
CUR_ILL: Allergy to intravenous contrast media (highly allergic, has to be pre-medicated 2 to 3 days before use); Drug allergy (Sulfa drugs); Hypertension (approximately 30 years); Penicillin allergy
HISTORY: Medical History/Concurrent Conditions: Sodium abnormal NOS

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Passed out; Things were going downhill; Dizzy; Injection site was painful; Fatigued; Muscle pain; Joint pain; Nausea without vomiting; Low grade fever; A bit of an ache in injection arm; A spontaneous report was received from a consumer concerning a 79-year-old female patient who received Moderna's COVID-19 vaccine (mRNA-1273) and experienced the following:  things were going downhill, injection site was painful, fatigued, muscle pain, joint pain, nausea without vomiting, low grade fever, dizzy,  passed out, and a bit of an ache in her injection arm.  The patient's medical history was not provided. No concomitant medications were reported.    On 19-Feb-2021, prior to the onset of the events, the patient received their second of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 (lot/batch: 032L20a) intramuscularly for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection.  On 19-Feb-2021, the patient received the vaccine around noon and by the evening she could tell things were going downhill. She went to bed early, and throughout the night the injection site was painful, she was fatigued, she had muscle pain, joint pain, nausea without vomiting, and a low grade fever. The patient got up at night to go to the bathroom and got dizzy and passed out. She said she was passed our for barely a minute and when she came too she laid there for a bit before she went back to bed with her husband's help. All day on Saturday 20-Feb-2021 the patient was in bed but by that evening she was able to get up and walk out of the bedroom. On Sunday night 21-Feb-2021, she was able walk up stairs without huffing and puffing and felt much better. The patient states they have recovered from it all except sometimes when doing yoga, they can feel a bit of an ache in the injection arm.  No treatment information was provided.   The patient received both scheduled doses of mRNA-1273 prior to the event(s); therefore, action taken with the drug in response to the event(s) is not applicable.  The outcome of the events things were going downhill, injection site was painful, fatigued, muscle pain, joint pain, nausea without vomiting, low grade fever, dizzy, and passed out, were considered recovered/resolved.    The outcome of the event, ache in injection arm, was unknown.; Reporter's Comments: This case concerns a 79 Y/O F with a serious unexpected event of loss of consciousness along with NS unexpected dizziness, feeling abnormal, pain in extremity, and NS expected fever, fatigue, myalgia, arthralgia, nausea, vaccination site pain. Event onset the same day as second dose mRNA-1273. Events resolved except arm pain. Based on current available information and temporal association between use of the product and the start date of the event, a causal relationship cannot be excluded.

Very sensitive now to regular meds; lower back felt really heavy; pounding sensation up and down my torso; feeling of muscle heaviness that I almost felt paralyzed; extreme body ache; chills; I had a bad headache; stinging on both sides of my head and on hands and feet; was very lethargic; arm became real sore and was painful; This is a spontaneous report from a contactable consumer (patient). A 71-year-old female patient received their first dose of bnt162b2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 VACCINE; lot number: EL3249, expiry date not reported), via an unspecified route of administration on the left arm on 27Jan2021 10:30 at single dose for covid-19 immunisation. Medical history included mild lupus, post concussion syndrome (PPCs) and allergies: sulfur (very sensitive to large doses) from an unknown date and unknown if ongoing.  Concomitant medication included esomeprazole magnesium (NEXIUM), tramadol, alprazolam and acetylsalicylic acid (ALKA SELTZER). The patient reported that after just a few hours on 27Jan2021, their arm became real sore and was painful to use until next morning, was sore for 2 days. Hurt after much normal use. Woke up on the morning of 28Jan2021 (3 am) with chills, extreme body ache and feeling of muscle heaviness that they almost felt paralyzed. They could still move. They had a bad headache and stinging on both sides of their head and on hands and feet. They took aspirin and went back to sleep. When they got up they felt some better, but did not feel well and was very lethargic. That night they took another aspirin before bed. On the morning of 29Jan2021 (second day ) they again woke up at 3 AM to extreme body ache, the same heavy paralyzing feeling, but this time their lower back felt really heavy and there was a pounding sensation up and down their torso. They repeated the aspirin dose and went back to bed but did not sleep anymore that day. They did feel some better but still very lethargic. Next day better, but took 5 days to feel some normal w/o fatigue. The patient is very sensitive now to regular meds. Therapeutic measures were taken which included aspirin. The patient was recovering from feeling of muscle heaviness that I almost felt paralyzed, extreme body ache, chills, headache, stinging on both sides of my head and on hands and feet, lethargy recovered from arm became real sore and was painful on an unspecified date, while the outcome of the other events was unknown. The patient was not diagnosed with COVID prior to vaccination and has not been tested for COVID since vaccination.
HISTORY: Medical History/Concurrent Conditions: Drug allergy (very sensitive to large doses); Lupus erythematosus; Post concussion syndrome

SYMPTOM_TEXT: has not smell or taste a lot of the time; has not smell or taste a lot of the time; sight is not clear; flipped out; her blood pressure went up while she was in the Emergency room; panicked; Lightheadedness; Weakness; felt a little tired at that time; atrial fibrillation/started racing/Heartbeats irregular; anxiety; couldn't breathe/shortness of breath/hard time breathing; it was cold outside by her nephew's graveside, but she felt she had to fan herself like she was overheated; her heart rate was flying; scared; she said it was not a migraine headache like she is used to, but more of a mild headache; This is a spontaneous report from a contactable consumer (patient herself). A 77-year-old female patient received BNT162B2 (Pfizer-BioNTech COVID-19 mRNA vaccine, Batch/lot number: EM9801), via an unspecified route of administration on the left arm, first dose on 04Feb2021 (Administered between 9:30-10:00AM) at single dose for COVID-19 immunisation.  Medical history included chronic migraines all her life. She said her migraines have let up as she has gotten older. She also had an irregular heart rate before, saying her irregular heart rate started in her adult life. She said she considered herself more of a "carrier" for an irregular heart rate because her irregular heart rate doesn't happen enough for her to think about it. She said she doesn't have an irregular heart rate now. She said her father had a pacemaker & her 2 brothers had heart problems; her oldest brother passed away from his heart problems & her other brother has blood pressure issues. Patient also had mild asthma as an adult. She said she worked at (name) in a dusty environment, and lived near a landfill, where a lot of her neighbors have gotten sick. She said she needs an inhaler for her asthma. She said when she needs the inhaler, she takes 3-4 puffs at a time. She said she doesn't use the inhaler every day and also mentioned that her grandfather had died of a bad asthma attack. No previous immunization with the Pfizer vaccine considered as suspect. No vaccines administered on the same date of vaccine. No prior vaccinations within 4 weeks. There were no concomitant medications. On 13Feb2021, the patient experienced an atrial fibrillation in which she started racing and couldn't breathe. She mentioned that she recently attended a funeral but attributed the symptoms as side effects of the vaccine. She was taken to the Emergency room where she was given cortisone and resolved her symptoms. Patient also further  reported she had side effects with the Pfizer COVID-19 Vaccine. She clarified she had her first COVID-19 Vaccine dose on 04Feb2021. She said her side effects happened less than 14 days after getting the COVID-19 Vaccine. Patient thought her side effects from the COVID-19 Vaccine may have been anxiety within. She said her nephew had died of COVID-19, and when she was at his funeral at the graveside, she flipped out while she was at her nephew's funeral, she was not doing good. She said she has a history of chronic migraines, and mild asthma. She said she had to lean against a gravestone because she couldn't breath. She said it was cold outside by her nephew's graveside, but she felt she had to fan herself like she was overheated. She said her heart rate was flying, and she had an irregular heart beat. She said she left her nephew's graveside and went to an urgent care. She said the doctor at the urgent care had done an EKG result abnormal, and told her she needed to go to the Emergency Room right away. She said the doctor had called the paramedics to transport her from the urgent care to the Emergency Room at (Institute name). She said she did not have any pain, but had a hard time breathing. She said she may have been scared because her grandfather had died of a bad asthma attack. She said she has chronic migraines, but what she had at the time was a mild headache, and not a migraine. She said she has not smell or taste a lot of the time. She clarified she has had no smell or taste for a while, saying she would not be able to tell if she got the COVID-19 Virus because of her loss of taste and smell. She said she was tested the Friday before her nephew's funeral and was negative for the COVID-19 Virus. She said she has had a total of four COVID-19 Virus tests before, and all her COVID-19 Virus tests have been negative. She clarified she did not have a COVID-19 Virus test while she was at the ER on Saturday, 13Feb2021. With her nephew's death, getting her COVID-19 Vaccine had left her mind. She said it didn't dawn on her until she settled down, and she thought her high heart rate and irregular heart beat were side effects of the COVID-19 Vaccine. She said she read the paperwork that was given to her at the time she got the COVID-19 Vaccine. She said the side effects listed for the COVID-19 Vaccine is what she had, a very fast heart beat, and it was very hard for her to breath. She said the Emergency Room doctor didn't think to ask her about the COVID-19 Vaccine. She said she panicked when she got to the hospital. She said she didn't even know that someone had drew blood from her. She said someone put a label on her, and told her the label was to show blood was drawn from her. She said when she looked down at the label, she saw an IV access was put in her arm. Additional treatment reported when she was in the Emergency Room, she was given an injection (clarified as IVPB on 13Feb2021) of Diltiazem 120mg at 12:13:50 PM, she said she was given another Diltiazem 5mg injection at the same time. She clarified she was diagnosed in the Emergency Room with Atrial Fibrillation. Patient stated that her blood pressure went up while she was in the Emergency room. She said she was kept in the Emergency Room so she could be monitored up until that evening. She said after the Diltiazem injections were given, her heart rate went down. She said the Emergency Room doctor gave her a prescription for Diltiazem 120mg white capsules, and told her to take the Diltiazem 120mg every day. She said the emergency room doctor told her she could go home, and that she needed to follow-up with her regular doctor. Reported she no longer has the shortness of breath, lightheadedness, or weakness. She said had felt a little tired at that time, as well. Patient also reported that on 22Feb2021 was her first day outside of her house since last Sunday (14Feb2021) and reported she has a slight headache, and her sight is not clear. She said she now feels she has "name" back, clarifying she has recovered completely. She has a follow up with her doctor on 24Feb2021. She is scheduled to take her 2nd dose on 04Mar2021 and is asking if she should take anything before the shot. Vaccination Facility Type was a pharmacy/drug store. Vaccine was not administered at Facility. The outcome of the events was recovered on an unspecified date.

Two days after injection pain started at site of injection.   Pain increased daily for about 3 days.  Five days after injection a reddish-pink area started up.   Pain & red area persisted and after 3 weeks the left elbow developed a pain on a bone protruding .   In December went to Doctor... He said the elbow pain would go away (and eventually it did).  He diagnosed the pink area as the result of my scratching it and advised me to stop and put euricin cream on it which I continue to do today.  I favor the arm somewhat to prevent pain and to keep from dropping things.   The injection (and pain) site appears to me to be at the lower point of the deltoid muscle, well below the shoulder edge.  I seldom scratch it as it does not itch.  The doctor thought I was scratching it as every time I tried to show him where it was at he thought I was getting ready to scratch it.  The pain continues today.
OTHER_MEDS: Isosorbide 15mg; Metaprolol 50mg; Tamsulosin 0.4mg; Atorvastatin 20mg; Amlidopine 5mg; Metformin 500mg.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: about two hours after injection,  I experienced headache,  then mild dizziness,  then extreme dizziness,  then sudden overwhelming fatigue,  then swollen eyes and eyelids,  then chills and elevated heart rate,  with pounding.    I had to cancel the class I was supposed to teach,  because I would not have been safe to drive to campus.  I slept from approximately 2:30 pm on March 8 until 8:30 am today,  March 9,   all symptoms continuing,  with bathroom breaks, a couple of short reports to family members who were watching out for me,  and one  2-hour window during which I ate a small meal,  went back to bed,  and read part of a book.    During bathroom breaks I took more antronex,  some milk thistle,  and some glutathione,  which seemed to at least temporarily reduce dizziness and eye/eyelid swelling. I have been a registered nurse for over 12 years. Recently, on Thursday February 18th, my PCR came back positive. Immediately after on February 19th, I went for another PCR and a RAPID, and BOTH were negative. I have been asymptomatic since the start of the pandemic and fully vaccinated since January 18th. When the contact tracers called me, they told me they do not take into account the fact that I am fully vaccinated and swabbed negative. In fact, none of this data is being collected. As a medical professional I think this information should be collected and is imperative information to collect to move forward from this pandemic. None of my contacts in my household or otherwise have gotten COVID since I tested positive.  I was told by the department of health I have to self-quarantine even though I am negative and fully vaccinated, and that they do not take into account my vaccination status or negative swab.  I contacted the cdc and the NYS DOH and political leaders. I heard back from the CDC saying they set guidelines. Clearly some states are not following them. I still get swabbed weekly although I am vaccinated.  Many of my fully vaccinated colleagues in the long term care facility have been in the exact same situation, being tested having a positive PCR then immediately negative. No one in their household or contacts tested positive either.

On the night of  February 25 (day 6/7) I woke up in the middle of the night with my hands itching and right butt cheek.  In the morning, there were a couple  small hives between my fingers on left hand and a larger one on right butt cheek.  I was able to go about my day, periodically itching.  That night, I woke up more frequently in the night with both hands itching.  Primarily in between my fingers and a few small hives on both ankles.  At 11 AM, I noticed a lesion on my tongue.  By Friday night I had several more spots and the itching continued to become more bothersome.  I took benadryl before bed.  I woke up Saturday morning at 1 AM with my tongue swollen and  lower right lip swollen as well.  These did not itch nor hurt.  My hands itched and burned very intensely, I put ice on them for some relief.  There were more hives on my hands, ankles,  left shin and left knee and right elbow.  I went into urgent care at 9 am.  Dr prescribed Prednisone and benadryl.  Dr. only looked at my hands and mouth.  When I got home I noticed I had a large hive bout 2" by 4"above the injection site on my right arm.  This did itch, however was not a major concern because my hands hurt quite severely.  I took benedryl at noon on Saturday and that did bring the swelling of my lips and tongue down.  I could not sleep at all on Saturday night due to the pain and itching.  Once the prednisone took effect, I finally got some relief.  Monday I went to see the allergist and he also prescribed zrytek twice a day.  He suggested I take that for a few weeks to make sure the hives do not return.  It is March 9 and some of the hives are still there and bothersome, but the majority have resolved.

Patient came in for Janssen COVID vaccine that was scheduled electronically online.  All appropriate prescreening was done and patient had no previous allergies or issues.  Patient was instructed to sit in one of the chairs designated for post vaccine observation for 15 minutes after her vaccine.  Within a minute or so  patient felt light headed and like she might pass out. She notified the technician who was right there and he notified me.  I assisted her to a sitting position on the floor from her chair and I was able to ease her back to a lying down position from there with her head on the floor and feet elevated above heart on a chair.  Patient was able to talk the whole time.  She told us at that point when she was younger she was scared of shots and had fainted when having them, but thought she was past that and did not mention it during screening. She said she was surprised to feel this way because she was so excited about getting her COVID vaccine.  She had not eaten much today (a small snack) and had rushed here for her appointment without getting food. I checked her blood pressure while she was lying down and it was 94/63 and pulse of 75.  She said she normally had lower end of normal blood pressure.   She was pale when I started checking her, but her color began to return to normal within minutes. After 5 minutes she felt well enough to sit up and we got her a granola bar and water.  She remained this way for 5 minutes and felt good, so we moved her to sitting in a chair and got her a pepperoni and cheese snack tray from the cafe.  She ate this and waited for 10minutes and felt good. We walked her to her car and she felt fine.  I called to verify she got home fine and she did.
PRIOR_VAX: She has fainted before and has a fear of needles.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient came in for Janssen COVID vaccine that was scheduled electronically online.  All appropriate prescreening was done and patient had no previous allergies or issues.  Patient was instructed to sit in one of the chairs designated for post vaccine observation.  Within minutes (less than 3), patient was very dizzy, clammy (cold sweats), pale and said he did not feel right.  I assisted him to a sitting position on the floor from his chair and we were able to ease him back to a lying down position from there with his head on the floor and feet elevated above heart on a chair.  Patient said that the cold floor actually made him feel better instantly.  At 4:18pm after lying down for about 3 minutes we checked his blood pressure with him still lying down.  It was 110/88 and pulse of 104 (so slightly elevated pulse).  He said he was feeling better and we kept him lying down.  Patient's wife was also there so she was able to provide information in addition to him doing it also.  She did state that he occasionally had panic attacks and she thought this might be one, the patient was adamant that it was not.  At 4:24 pm we checked his blood pressure again and it was 100/90 and Pulse of 104.  He was feeling quite a bit better so we had him come to a sitting position on the floor and he had not eaten in a while so we got him a granola bar and water.  Pt slowly ate these and begin to feel clammy and sweaty again within 3-4 minutes. We checked his blood pressure again and it was 104/90 and pulse of 100.  He wanted to stay sitting to see if it would pass.  We did continuously observe injection site and screen for any other symptoms of an allergic reaction (nausea, cramping, swelling, and none of these were occurring). Since he was still not feeling well we gave the patient 50mg of benadryl (20 mls of 12.5mg/5ml liquid benadryl) with his approval. After about 10 minutes of sitting total he was still having cold sweats and feeling dizzy so we had him lie back on his back with his feet elevated while the benadryl kicked in.  By 4:50pm he was feeling well enough to sit back up and we got him some wraps and a coke from the cafe to eat.  Pt continued to consistently improve and was ready to leave about 5:20pm.  We advised him and his wife of signs and symptoms of allergic reaction and to have those treated to immediately at urgent care or and ER.   We also told him to follow-up with his PCP.  I had a manager help walk them to their car.  They were very kind and grateful.  I will follow-up with a call tomorrow and again on Friday to make sure he continues to do well.

Beginning the day after my injection (2/27), I experienced soreness in my left shoulder above injection site. The following day, the soreness migrated to my neck on the left side. This stiffness and pain lasted 9 days. On the 10th day after my injection (3/8/21), I experienced a sudden full-body welting rash that spread very quickly. I tool zyrtec and allegra to try to stop it, but the rash is still present today (3/9/21). I had a rapid test done today for confirmation that it was not a sign of the actual covid-19 virus because it looks like several reported images, but the test came back negative. Initially, the rash was very uncomfortable. It felt like a stinging itch, and my skin was hot to the touch. It was red, splotchy, raised, and felt like a sun burn. Today, the rash is still visible, not as raised or red, but can still be felt and is a lighter shade of red. My skin is not as hot to the touch, but still warmer over the raised parts of the rash. It does not hurt, but if loose clothing rubs on it, or I accidentally scratch it, it does start to itch  and get irritated. I do have pictures of the different stages in progression if needed.

Initial troponin is nonnegative at 0.05.  ACS seems unlikely.  Plan to repeat troponin. Lactate is not elevated.  Urine shows a large number of leuk esterase and 8 WBCs.  There are no bacteria or nitrates and no red cells.  We will proceed with a urine culture. TSH is normal. Repeat troponin was undetected.  Ultrasound shows no evidence for DVT bilaterally.  There is a linear hypoechoic focus in the left proximal femoral vein which is favored to be calcification or less likely chronic post thrombotic change. There is no hilar lymphadenopathy or suspicious bony lesions.  There is mild fat stranding in the anterior mesentery of the upper abdomen.  There is no known history of malignancy.  CT abdomen pelvis shows no acute findings.  There are no masses or acute inflammatory process."  She presented back to the ER on February 23 with left eye droop and jaw tenderness x3 to 4 days. Very sore arm starting about 4 ours post injection.  Couldn't raise it above shoulder level.  Felt very thick and heavy.  Throbbing.  Pulsating, as though I could feel my heartbeat in my arm when I went to bed.  Took to Tylenol or sleep would have been impossible.  Woke up to a less painful arm and it improved throughout day feeling almost normal by bedtime 24 hours later.  Took 2 Tylenol to ensure sleep.  Woke up Tuesday morning and arm felt almost 2100% normal.  I thought, wow, that wasn't so bad.  BUT I WAS WRONG.  Tuesday mid morning, I began to feel what I would describe as jittery.  Around 11:00 am a wave of nausea washed over me and subsided.  I thought maybe I needed to eat as I hadn't yet so I had lunch.  After lunch I began to feel nauseous again and like diarrhea was coming.  After going to the bathroom, the nausea started building again,  and the diarrhea recurred, and the nausea heightened.  By mid afternoon I was on the floor hugging the toilet bowl wanting to vomit, waiting to vomit, groaning.  It's been years since I've had nausea or vomiting and the whole experience was unexpected from what I read about possible reactions.  I wondered if it was food poisoning but my husband and I had eaten the same thing and he was fine.  Finally about 3:30-4:00, 48 ours post vaccine, I threw up multiple times, perhaps 5 times.    After about 4:30 pm it was over.  I was worried that if I ate again I'd be sick so I only drank decaf tea.  I felt exhausted from the ordeal but very wired and jittery too.  I crawled into bed hoping for sleep.  No luck.  At 3:00 am I was still watching the clock and shocked that I couldn't sleep.  I had to get up at 6:30 in the morning due to some construction at our home.  I was legit exhausted Wednesday.  I no recurrence of the nausea or diarrhea after the bout on Tuesday afternoon.  I ate modestly but normally on Wednesday and slept normally Wednesday night.    Nothing more to report, although I read that up to a week later some people experienced a reaction so I wanted to give it a week to see if anything else would happen.  Nothing else to report.

30 hours after vaccine a warm, red, hard marking, approximately 3 inched in diameter , appeared at the injection site. Treatment was Ibuprophen and Ice. The next morning the mark spread, appeared lighter, warm and hard to the touch. As the day progressed my arm felt heavy, by the afternoon my arm and hand (not the red spot) felt cold. That evening my shoulder to my fingertips were numb with a "falling asleep" sensation. I still had control of movement but was unable to feel any touch. I wrapped a heating pad around my arm for two hours, unable to feel the heat, and took Ibuprofen and Benadryl. Around 11:00 that night I was able to feel my pinky finger. Continued to apply heat every 20 minutes for 20 minutes throughout the night and continued with ibuprofen and Benadryl. The next morning I was able to feel my ring finger, the red spot had disappeared, and the hardness was decreasing. That evening, continuing with heat, Ibuprofen, and Benadryl, I was able to feel 4 fingers. Continued into Sunday with same treatment and by Sunday morning I was able to feel my entire hand and wrist. As the day progressed I regained feeling up to my elbow and the shoulder by the night. Monday I discontinued treatment. Had full feeling of my arm, with pain in my elbow and shoulder. Tuesday morning all was back to normal.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The shot was given to me (Sat) in the upper (L) arm about 2 -1/2 inches down from top of shoulder.  It was a simple prick however I thought it seemed an odd location.  About 24 hours later (Sun) I felt first signs of tenderness at the site but didn't think much of it as that is what I had heard from others about the vaccine.  Later in the day it became achy.  On Monday morning I noticed my whole arm was achy in addition to the top of my shoulder and the left side of my neck and  upper shoulder blade.  At 9:30 am I felt very tired and laid down and awoke 4 hours later!  My aches were still all there as though I had slept wrong.  Again I was not too concerned except that my friends all said their discomfort was gone within 24 hrs.  Today is Tuesday and evening and as I sit here I have a very tender, sore, achy upper left arm and a small black and blue spot at the site.  It's strange because it doesn't hurt when I touch it, instead it is just an ache/pain that I feel and especially when I move the arm.  The tightness and ache in my neck and back and shoulder has lessened.  I am reporting as I was not expecting this type of reaction especially to last  3-1/2 days so far.  I feel this adverse reaction probably has more to do with the location that the technician chose to give me the vaccine.  I am thinking the muscles are reacting to injection.

He also was in the hospital for something with toxins. He had a lung problem for a long time. If he didn't go to the bathroom the toxins were hitting the liver and then the toxins were going to the brain. When he was in the hospital he couldn't eat or swallow. The first day he did eat a bit, but he had dialysis in the hospital, and it knocks him out. They were giving him antibiotics IV. He couldn't swallow any of his pills. He was in there for 11 days and had not eaten. He couldn't swallow any pills. He started going to sleep and they started giving him Morphine drip at the end. They couldn't get any medicine in him because he couldn't swallow. The patient died of pneumonia, the outcome of the other adverse events was unknown. SYMPTOM_TEXT: At 1405, Patient was sitting in observation room after receiving first dose of Pfizer. Patient slide down from the chair to the floor and was assisted by her grandmother as well. I immediately went to the patient aide, and she awoke quickly to my voice.  I asked the patient for her name and she stated her name. I asked her DOB and she identified her DOB.  I asked her if she had any allergies and she denied. I asked the patient if she had any medical conditions, and she denied. I asked the patient if she has ever fainted before and she stated "yes", she has an extreme fear of needles. I also asked the patient if she had eaten anything and she stated, yes, we just had lunch. While I was asking the patient these questions, I assessed the Patient pulse and it was 110, and respiratory was 16.  I then asked the patient to focus on her breathing and took the patient Vital Signs. 138/58, HR 78, Resp 16.Auscultated anterior fields, lungs were. clear, no advantageous sounds heard. The patient remained on the floor while asking the questions and assessing the patient. The charge nurse and the LVN, placed the patients feet up on the chair. I then asked the patient how she felt and she stated she was fine, I assisted the patient to a sitting position and asked her how she felt and she stated fine, and then we went to a standing position and she stated she was fine. I then assisted the patient to the chair, provided water and also a cool ice pack.  Patient continued to have normal conversation with myself and her grandmother.  A few minutes later, the patient appear to look like she was going to vomit, I then immediately provided the trash can to the patient. I also assisted the patient with cleaning the patients hands and right arm, where vomit was. Provided Clean hand wipes, and hand sanitizer. The patient remained stable, and 30 minutes later walked to the car with her grandmother and went home.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Because of the absurd character limit in this field, I am putting my adverse reaction statement on the continuation page. About 10pm, about 9 hours post injection, I was feeling weak and fatigued.  I went to bed and was starting to feel chilled, but not shaking.  I hopped into bed and turned on my electric blanket in a room that was 75� (from passive solar house heating during the day) and wearing only a T-shirt, sweat shirt, and sweat pants.  The first post-vaccination symptom I experienced was when I laid down and my right upper arm (at the point of the injection) was very sore; it was too painful to lie on my right side.  The injection area felt hard. I fell asleep about 11pm and woke up about midnight; I am generally a very light sleeper, rarely sleeping more than ~3� hours (most less than) at a time.  At 1:30am, I could not sleep so I watched a recorded movie.  All the while, I was feeling progressively worse.  About 2:30am, I felt really chilled, so I cranked up the electric blanket to its highest setting and put on some heavy wool socks, a pair of long-johns under my sweat pants, put on another heavy sweatshirt over my existing sweatshirt, and placed another blanket on top of my electric blanket: very cold / chilled but not shivering.  The movie ended about 3am, and my stomach was excruciatingly aching.  I did not feel I could eat anything which I really felt a need to do, but was concerned that I would just vomit.  However, I did take two, 500mg Tylenol tablets with a half a glass of water.  I might have slept for an hour or so, but was quite restless.  I remember looking at the clock at 4:00am.  By 5am, it was considering calling 911; my stomach ached so badly.  It was then, that I had the feeling / recollection I had this "illness" before.  About 5:30am, my stomach symptoms started to ameliorate; by 7:30am, they were gone.  However, I still felt miserable.  I then wondered whether my stomach symptom was just a concomitant bout with "stomach flu" where I experienced (severe) abdominal cramps and pain; nausea; and low-grade fever.  I have had the stomach flu a limited number of times before and, after 6� hours, it all went away: I just had to suck it up in the meantime.  Before I filled out this report, I wanted to consider whether my stomach flu was a reaction to the vaccination or incidental to the vaccination.  However, after talking with my neighbors and my sister's friend, who also had the Moderna vaccination, three of the four "victims" had similar symptoms to me.  Thus, I deduced I did not have a bout with stomach flu.  Additionally, a dog walking partner, who is a rescue worker, also noted folks she knew also had similar symptoms with the Moderna vaccine.  I then started wondering what kind of artificial cocktail, a.k.a.: antifreeze, was the suspending medium for the vaccine.  If this has to be stored at absurdly low temperatures� I commonly have negative reactions to artificial chemicals.  The minor surgeries I have had are uneventful but for the anesthesia chemical concoction I am given.  I commonly takes me more then 2-3 days to detoxify that and feel �normal.'  As in this case, I pretty much laid in bed for the next 2� days, with no energy or desire to attend to personal issues, including walking my dogs.  However, my subclinical temperature was pretty much gone after the second day.  The notable soreness in my arm was mostly gone after two days, but the injection point was still sensitive to pressing on top of the injection site: I could still feel it.  I have a very high tolerance for pain and have never experienced anything like this.  "Pain" from flu, etc., shots rarely, if ever, lasts more than 10-15 minutes post injection.  There was definitely something in the suspension media that reacted with my body chemistry / biological processes.  I am NOT looking forward to the booster shot; most seem to have a reaction to the second shot that is worse than the first � unless their first shot was uneventful and the second shot had considerably milder reactions than my first shot.  The next time I will definitely have a bowl or two of jell-O in the refrigerator to help quell any (expected) gut reactions; jell-O has always been a comfort food for me in those situations. What a horribly designed survey�.  This is next to impossible to complete online.  After timing out twice, I had to start over and opted to download the fillable form PDF.  Even then, I am not given the option to select the subdirectory _where_ it should be downloaded.  Fortunately, I saw the option to open it directly. If you are going to make the "adverse reaction" field so limited, relative to field size and the absurd online time limit, how can you expect meaningful, complete reporting of post-vaccination reactions?  This form CANNOT be fully completed in the time allotted without timing out.  This is, most certainly, a deterrent to adverse reaction reporting.  One has to wonder how many folks just gave up after getting timed out the first time. With this kind of disincentive, how good or complete or meaningful is the adverse data collection procedure?  Have you purged all the supporters?  They do not like real, accurate, objective data, particularly information that is not consistent what they want to believe or the narrative they want to spin.  No respectable scientist or decent journalist would accept third-rate data.  How can public interest decisions be made with a shoddy data collection effort?

Within 1-2 minutes of receiving the vaccine in my right arm (while sitting in the passenger seat of our car), my husband pulled forward in the lot, and I immediately felt a wave of heat come from my chest, up through my neck and into my face. I started sweating, got light-headed, very nauseous, and the left side of my face (everything under my cheekbone) felt "tingly". When we parked, I opened the car door, we opened the windows I drank water, and did some deep breathing. If I had been standing up after the shot, I think I would have fainted. I'm not sure what that reaction was.......I have had similar reactions when I've had my triptan-class injection medication or even the triptan medication in pill form. In those instances, I think my blood pressure dropped because of the vasodilation . I am not scared of shots, needles, or getting blood drawn at all. It wasn't fear and I had eaten plenty that morning as well as drank a lot of water. As far as the numbless/tingly feeling in my face, I do have damage to my trigeminal nerve that occurred during my craniotomy in 2016, so that area doesn't ever feel 100% normal, however the change to a more intense "tingliness" after the injection was pronounced and lasted about 3-4 days.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: A 63-year-old female with a medical history of Hashimoto?s Disease, on Levothyroxine 88 micrograms (4 days per week) and 100 micrograms (3 days per week), presented to the emergency department with a 7-day history of acute onset of severe, debilitating, fatigue, weakness, anorexia and malaise. She had no clear precipitating events, stated that she was in her usual states of health, active, working as an optometrist at a University hospital. Stated that 1 week before symptom oncer she had her first dose of Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine EUA. Stated that 24hrs later her symptoms started associated with low grade subjective fever, however her fever disappeared, and she persisted with severe fatigue. She was unable to do her regular activities of daily living and was hoping her symptoms would resolve but upon persistence and given the severity of her complains she presented to evaluation. She denied recently starting any new medications/supplements, or recent change in her levothyroxine dose. There were no headaches, cough, diarrhea, sore throat, rhinorrhea, myalgia, arthralgia, weakness, recent infectious illness or sick contacts. She was diagnosed with Hashimoto?s Disease over 10 years prior and had been on the same dose for more than 2 years.   VS were stable and within normal limits, physical exam was only remarkable for weakness on 4 extremities 4/5, lethargy, bradylalia, bilateral ptosis, no focal neurologic deficits, sensation intact. Laboratory workup revealed normal Hb 14.8, normal renal and kidney function, normal cortisol level, TSH normal 3.7, normal FT4: 1.2, normal CPK, negative tox screen. ESR and CRP were performed, and both were found to be elevated ESR 74, CRP 28, at that moment we decided to do immunologic workup showing high titers of ANA >1:320 with a nuclear speckled pattern, and a positive rheumatoid factor 60. At this point a full rheumatologic panel was performed which was negative for anti-Ach receptor Abs, negative anti-CCP, anti- dsDNA, anti-smith, negative anti-Jo1, anti-RNP, negative anti-TPO, negative anti-SCL70, normal C4 and C3 however elevated total CH50 > 60, positive anti-SSA and anti-SSB. Her symptoms of severe fatigue persisted throughout her admission and it was decided to give her a course of prednisone 40mg for 5 days and follow up as outpatient with a Rheumatologist. Repeat workup 2 weeks after discharge showed still elevated ESR at 72, high CRP 17, rheum factor elevated again at 67.  At this point no clear cause was identified as she did not have any symptoms of Sjogren or anything else other than severe persisting fatigue.  Another course of steroids was given and 1 month later she stated that she was much improved and was able to go back to work. Stated that she would not take her second covid MODERNA vaccine dose due to fear of recurrence of symptoms. It appeared that this vaccine triggered a severe inflammatory and autoimmune reaction in this patient with history of Hashimoto?s disease. The association between MODERNA vaccine and development of autoimmunity and inflammatory reaction needs to be assessed.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Following the vaccine she was at the grocery store around 5:00 PM, her granddaughter asked her why her mask was red, and she noticed that she had a dripping nose bleed, and left and by the time she got home it was done.   Then, 2/21/21, she had another nose bleed, was at a pizza place in the car, and felt like she had to spit and it was blood and had a smaller nose bleed that did not last night.  The next one 2/26/21, was in the store and had a dripping nose bleed again, took a while to get it stopped, but by the time she left the store she was fine.  Then Saturday 2/27/21, she kept getting up in the night and had nose bleeds off and on, and managed through the night and the morning.  She went to the ER in the morning on 2/28/21, and her nose was packed with dissolving packing and gave her a prescription for 3 pills to take to prevent her from getting an infection.    During the night Sunday night she had a very bad night and went to the ER again on 3/1/21 at around 5:00 AM.  They then packed her nose with a balloon and then got the first prescription filled that she took.  On Wednesday she went back to the ER and they removed the balloon and now has been fine.  Her Coumadin has been up and down during this period of time.  Her INR reading was 4.5 on 2/28/21, and subsequently has gone down to where it is quite low.  No issues with the injection site.  She has never had nosebleeds prior to the vaccine.   In October/November she had a procedure she had a hernia repair and had a COVID test and since then she has had a tinge on tissue, but not a nose bleed.   These were mainly on the right until she had the profuse one, and then it was both nostrils as well as coming out of her mouth.   Has an appointment with the ENT on 3/18/21.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient is an 81-year-old female with a past medical history of COPD on 3 L home oxygen, hypertension, tobacco use that presents to the ED for evaluation of shortness of breath.  Patient states that she felt short of breath after receiving the Covid vaccine just prior to arrival to the ED.  Patient states her symptoms are mild, constant, nonradiating, worse with exertion and no alleviating factors.  She denies associated fever, chills, chest pain, nausea, vomiting, diarrhea.  Patient states she is currently on prednisone therapy but does not know the dosage or duration.  She denies history of heart failure.
LAB_DATA: ED course: Patient presents to the ED with signs and symptoms consistent with COPD exacerbation community-acquired pneumonia.  Vitals are stable.  Exam demonstrates decreased breath sounds.  Patient was administered duo nebs, Solu-Medrol upon arrival.  Labs obtained are largely unremarkable, appear to be within patient's previously established baseline.  Chest x-ray is concerning for retrocardiac infiltrate.  Upon reevaluation, patient's breathing is stable, she is satting 95% on 3 dorsal oxygen which is her home oxygen requirement and she has no evidence of increased work of breathing in the ED.  Given her advanced age and comorbidity of COPD, she was offered admission to the hospital.  She declined admission and is with her son bedside who states that she has an appointment with her family doctor this upcoming week.  They prefer outpatient treatment and follow-up.  At this time we are in agreement for discharge home with outpatient antibiotic and steroid therapy.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Here is my story. Part 1: I had my second Moderna vaccine on 2/16. 36 hours later I was laying In bed when I all of a sudden felt very strange- sort of faint - like I was going to pass out. Then I started feeling like my Body was going numb. We called 911. I was taken to the ER. What followed was about 15-20 ?neurological? episodes (every ten minutes or so) where my entire body from head to toe became paralyzed- I couldn?t move any of my limbs. I also had no sight. I was not blacked out Bc I could hear everything that was happening. It was also accompanied by extreme chest pain, numbness, contratcing of muscles in chest cavity that felt almost like a heart attack. Each individual episode lasted about 3-5 minutes and then slowly the paralysis would undo and I?d regain feeling. And then the full episodes would start over a few minutes later. This went on for a few hours repeatedly while in the ER.  I was admitted for testing  and monitoring for two days (EEG, EKG, MRI, Catscan) all clear. Once discharged I had lingering neurological symptoms but not the full paralysis episodes. Lingering symptoms included severe chest pain, numbness/weaknesses predominant on the left side as well as other random areas. I was very weak and tired. I started to improve very slowly - by day 10 post hospitalization I was starting to feel like things were turning the corner and maybe I was on my way to recovery. Part 2: I started to finally feel more improved from the lingering neurological issues and then all of a sudden around 5:30PM I was in the kitchen making dinner for my kids on 3/2 and the episodes started again. Called 911. Again, every ten minutes or so they came on (maybe 15-18 episodes) of complete paralysis- this time accompanied by seizure like rapid eye movement from side to side and fluttering of the eyes. I was readmitted to the hospital where the episodes repeated to happen again, maybe 15-20 times. I was admitted. They did a 24 hour video EEG which ?caught? the episodes on video and sound but did not appear negatively on the EEG in terms of abnormal brain activity. I?ve been released as they say there is nothing to do. I have lingering muscle weakness in my eyes- I can?t focus my eyeballs or ?track? on an eye exam and continued muscular chest pain. I also have a lot of PTSD from the trauma of the events.
LAB_DATA: EEG, EKG, Electrocardiogram, MRI with and without Contrast, CT head,
OTHER_MEDS: Topamax, CBD pill, Xanax, Aimovig, Lo-Loestrin, Xyzal

I had heard you could have a slight reaction and I am usually pretty tough about being sick of which I am rarely.  But this one hit pretty hard.  I did not even get out of bed the entire time except to use the restroom.  I am not complaining, I just thought I would report my reaction if it would help.  I am absolutely thrilled that I received the vaccine and also the place that I received it was wonderful.   Everyone was very kind and efficient!  I was truly impressed and I will continue to encourage everyone I can to receive the vaccine.  Thank you.

Patient called via telephone at 4:53 p.m. on 2/26/2021. Patient reports that she was in for a 3:40 Covid-19 (Moderna) 1st dose shot appt.   She waited her allotted 15 minutes post vaccine before leaving. Patient denied ever having any reaction  to anything or vaccine in the past. Patient reports that once she was on her way home she started to experience nausea while driving home.  She also started to experience a weird kind of numb feeling that in time moved down in to her left arm, up her to the left side of her neck, jaw and eye. She felt like her eyelid might be drooping but she looked in the mirror and it wasn't.  She explained it as a "novacaine feeling" before it is fully numb.  "It starts in a spot then spread."  "Weird sensation, like going to the dentist.  Patient reported that she also has "weird skin" on her arm so can't really tell if there is a local rash.  Patient questioned if she can take Bendedryl and this PHN confirms that she can do that. PHN confirms that patient is not home alone and encouraged patient to follow up if she felt the need if her symptoms did not resolve or continue to spread or worsen.  Patient reports understanding of this.       1/26/2021: 6:30 p.m.  call update from patient.  This PHN called patient back and patient reports that she is lying low.  She took some Bendryl and it helped some. Patient continues to have a little bit of numbness and it did go in to her left teeth a little bit but the numb feeling isn't as bad as it    was.  PHN recommended that patient try to verify with her doctor before dose 2  of what happened and verify that it is okay to get her 2nd dose. PHN also informs patient that the is diphenhydramine ("Benedryl") on site that we can give her if needed when she is here for her 2nd dose.  PHN also recommends that if she comes in for her 2nd dose she would wait for 30 minutes post vaccination vs. the typical 15 minutes. 3/9/2021 telephone update from patient.   Patient contacted this PHN  to inform that she has had continued issues post Covid-19 vaccination.  Patient reports that she continues to have some numbness in the left side of her face and her BP continues to fluctuate up and down ranging from 182-90 to 142/?.  She has been in to doctor 2 times and has 1 more appointment scheduled.  She also is considering doing a neuro consult.  She did have testing done that ruled out a stroke.  Patient is unsure if she wants to follow through with  her 2nd.  PHN did not recommend patient getting her 2nd dose but encouraged her to have this discussion with her primary care provider

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Slight soreness in left arm around and just below the point of injection.  This went away around 6PM on Tuesday, the day after the injection.  For about 2 hours around 10PM until I went to sleep on Monday night (the night of the injection), I had a slight fever but it was only slight.  I had a more intense fever (though for only 30 minutes) the evening that I had my flu shot last October when I visited my doctor for a check up, so I would definitely categorize the fever from the COVID-19 shot as very slight.  It was gone when I woke up in the morning.  After I woke up, I was a bit nauseous, but it was so slight (and I have not been nauseous for well over a year) that it took me awhile to actually recognize it as being nauseous.  This lasted for 15-20 minutes and then it disappeared.  On Wednesday morning, my heart went into an irregular heartbeat that felt different than what I feel when it goes into an irregular heartbeat.  I have no idea if there is any relation between receiving the vaccine and getting an irregular heartbeat but I thought I should report it.  I have recovered from all symptoms from the vaccination except the irregular heartbeat.  I put down as "unknown" if I have recovered  from the adverse events as I don't know if going into an irregular heartbeat was in any way related to the vaccination.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 7 days after the shot, I developed what is termed ?Covid Arm?. It is a round, itchy, red rash around the injection site. I had another reaction within 24 hours of getting the shot, where the area around the injection site (about 4 inches) became red and swollen. I got my vaccine along with 2 other family members and I was the only one who had the red mark and severe swelling. My soreness also took much longer to go away.  After doing research and speaking with others online who have/had ?Covid Arm?, I believe if you gave them a head?s up that if they experience the redness around the injection site within 24 hours then they can probably expect to see ?Covid Arm? in 5 to 10 days. That seems to be the major sign of expecting that reaction. Although the people I talked to weren?t aware that the red area after injection wasn?t normal. Everyone I know personally that got this vaccine (the only one available to us), did not have the red area, so that definitely seemed to be part of the reaction.
LAB_DATA: Im a single mom and cannot afford health insurance so I won?t be seeing a doctor. I hope it goes away soon.
HISTORY: Bronchitis, depression, stress, degenerative disk disease.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I waited the requested 15 minutes as requested after my shot and felt fine although in hindsight i realize my finger joints were hurting/swelling. I left the facility as planned and while sitting at a red light  ( about 2 mins after leaving) my cheeks suddenly got very flushed and were burning. I looked in my car mirror they were bright red. The light turned green and I turned then under my chin suddenly felt like a bug bit it and started itching intensely. This sensation reminded me of the last time I reacted to a medication so I pulled into a parking lot and parked. i looked in the mirror again and my neck./ throat had angry red hives/rash all over it , my tongue and throat began feeling strange ( swelling?) and I felt very light headed and shaky. I drove back across the road to the vaccination clinic and showed a nurse. She said I was reacting to the shot. The nurses had me lay down and gave me benedryl. At that time my blood pressure was also very high  ( unusual , I usually have great blood pressure) . All of this happened in the 30 minutes of me leaving the clinic ( 11.00-11.30) I responded positively to the benedryl and my rash/hives and swelling subsided . I had a family member drive me home and I was advised to keep taking benedryl every 6 hrs. I woke up the next day ( March 9th) at 5.00 A.M expecting to feel ok and quickly realized i was really not feeling good. My entire body ached ,and my muscles all down my left side were incredibly painful to move. My joints hurt and my fingers and feet/toes were swollen. My neck /lymph nodes were also swollen and my rash on my neck came back for at 8.30 A.M ( I took more benedryl) . I also had an awful headache and fever and was exhausted. I ended up sleeping most of the day and could not go to work. I woke up at 5,00 A.M today ( March 10th ) and fel weak but much better

Medication Error NOT ADE  COVID vaccine clinic. vaccinator reported to pharmacy that she believes she administered a dose of 0.1ml to a patient as opposed to the necessary 0.5ml that is required.   Patient had left building by the time error was discovered.   We were able to identify who the patient was who received the underdose.  We contacted Janssen for recommendation on either administering the additional 0.4 mL dose or a full 0.5 mL dose.   Janssen had no recommendations for partial dosing, split dosing and we were instructed to follow up as we felt most appropriate.   We ultimately administered the additional 0.4 mL partial dose to the patient.    In reviewing incident with involved Pharmacy staff, it appears that unintentionally a 1 mL syringe was given to this vaccinator amongst the standard 3 mL syringes used to administer the 0.5 mL dose.  It was reported to me that the vaccinator self reported that when she was drawing up the intended dose of 0.5 mL she did not recognize that she was using a 1 mL syringe.  Vaccinator drew the dose back to the first major marking on the syringe (0.1mL).  On the 3 mL syringes the first major marking is 0.5 mL.    The Pharmacy staff reported that the 1 mL syringe packaging and the 3 mL syringe packaging are nearly identical.  After this incident Pharmacy staff segregated all 1 mL syringes to ensure 1 mL syringes were no longer supplied to any vaccinator.  Going forward Pharmacy, whenever possible,  will work to prevent any 1 mL syringes from being sent to a Moderna or J&J clinic were the doses are 0.5 mL.

By the end of the day, my arm was sore to the touch. The next morning, I had a 6 inch red, goose egg on the inside of my left arm, running from my elbow to armpit. While the swelling and tenderness subsided by the following Monday, I continued to have a series of sharp pains and dull aches in my left arm for weeks. I contacted the provider who thought that I had reacted to the preservative in the vaccine. After about 6 weeks of the ongoing pain, I had x-rays, saw an orthopedic doc, had an MRI, saw the orthopedic doc again, was referred to a pain management specialist (he wanted me to have another in-depth MRI with dye on my shoulder), have had massage therapy, seen a reflexologist twice, seen a chiropractic provider four times and now working with a kinesiologist twice a week to get my arm retrained and strengthened. I had absolutely no underlying health issues before the vaccine and following my visit with the pain management doc, he too believes my issues are directly related to this vaccine. Believe me, if I'd had any indication this would occur, I would never have agreed to this vaccination. Subsequently, I have had two Moderna vaccinations in the past 6 weeks with absolutely no side effects other than a bit of soreness in my arm the following day.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: herpes zoster oticus/Ramsey Hunt syndrome/vesicles in right ear/vertigo/problems with balance/ear pain; vomiting; Hearing loss; Shingles; Bell's Palsy/right sided facial weakness, tingling and numbness; This initial spontaneous report was received from a lawyer regarding a case in litigation and refers to a male patient of unknown age. No information was provided regarding concomitant medications, concurrent conditions or medical history. On or around 24-OCT-2014, the patient was inoculated with zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) for routine adult health maintenance and for its intended purpose: the prevention of shingles (dose, dose number, route, anatomical site of vaccination, lot # and expiration date were not provided). On an unknown date (reported as shortly after receiving the vaccine), the patient suffered vesicles in right ear, vomiting, vertigo, problems with balance, hearing loss, ear pain, right sided facia weakness, tingling and numbness and was diagnosed with shingles (herpes zoster), Bell's Palsy (facial paralysis), Ramsey Hunt syndrome and herpes zoster oticus (herpes zoster oticus). As a direct and proximate result of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient's symptoms had resulted in physical limitations not present prior to using the vaccine. The patient also experienced mental and emotional distress due to resulting physical limitations and seriousness of his condition. In addition, the patient sustained severe and permanent personal injuries. The outcome of Herpes zoster oticus, herpes zoster, vomiting, deafness and facial paralysis was not recovered. SYMPTOM_TEXT: History of Present Illness     89-year-old female with past medical history significant for osteoporosis and hypothyroidism, who initially presented to ER on March 2 due to lower extremity weakness and right knee pain after a recent fall.  Patient lost her balance and suffered a mechanical fall on February 22.  Patient developed right lumbar and hip pain radiating down her leg.  She saw Dr from orthopedics on February 26 who recommended offloading knee and wearing a knee immobilizer.  Patient was admitted to hospital on March 2 due to worsening knee pain and was incidentally found to be positive for COVID-19.  Patient had received her second Moderna COVID-19 vaccination on February 26.  Patient was evaluated by neurology during that hospital course, who recommended outpatient EMG, physical therapy, and pain management.  No evidence of Guillain-Barr� or viral induced neuropathy.  Patient's lower extremity weakness did improve, and she was successfully discharged home with family and home health on March 5.   Patient reports doing well at home with family initially, was making improvements with her strength and was able to stand and take a few steps with walker and assistance.  On March 8, patient was in bed and she attempted to turn onto her right side, and as she was turning she felt a pop and a pain in her right hip that radiated down her right leg.  Since that time, patient reports having severe pain with movement, rates pain as 8/10 severity.  Denies falls or new trauma since her previous fall from February 22.  Patient was unable to control pain at home, so she came into the emergency department for evaluation.  Initial hip x-ray series revealed questionable greater trochanteric fracture.  CT of right hip subsequently revealed fracture.  Orthopedics consulted.  No significant laboratory abnormalities.  Foley catheter was placed in ER.  Patient was admitted to hospital service for management.  On my interview, patient reports that right hip pain is under good control as long as she does not move, but has 7/10 pain severity over her right lateral hip with movement.   Patient reports following Covid isolation protocols at home with family.  Reports that her Covid isolation will be completed on March 12.  Denies upper respiratory symptoms.  Patient has oxygen saturations of 100% on room air.

***To continue off previous entries: VAERS E-REPORT 326730 AND E-REPORT*** I received the 1st dose of the Moderna Vaccine on January 6, 2021 at 01:49 pm. Approximately 4.5 hours later on January 6, 2021, I went outside in the cold temperatures. Upon returning inside to warmer air, the bilateral fingertips of both hands were pale white, numb, and painful. The time was 06:30 pm on January 6, 2021. At 06:47 pm, I felt a different feeling in the bilateral tips of my fingertips, and could see the color changing from pale white to a mixture of purple/black.  January 6, 2021 at 06:32 pm was the first time I have ever had my hands respond in this manner to cold temperatures. I have felt one fingertip go numb and turn white for a split second, only one time in my life but it was not a repeat occurrence, and it only lasted for about a second when it occurred. This experience and reaction I currently have lasts from 15-30 minutes of bilateral fingertip numbness and discoloration with pain. The bilateral fingertips of both hands now respond in this manner every time they are exposed to cold temperatures. I signed up for V-Safe and did state that I was having this symptom through the Vaccine reporting system on V-Safe under other'' multiple times. Treatment I received from a health provider are as follows; I had a telemedicine visit on January 14, 2021 at 12:51 pm to address my concern of ?reaction to Covid vaccine, fingertips were numb, lasting 30 mins?. On 1/14/2021, I received a primary diagnosis of Raynaud's Syndrome by my Primary Care Provider.  On 1/28/2021, I was seen in person by my Primary Care Provider for a Well Visit to complete a physical with my primary care provider. I was provided with a referral to a Rheumatologist for further advice about receiving the additional second Covid vaccination in the series. I also was ordered to do lab work. On 2/2/2021, I was seen by a Rheumatologist for new diagnosis of Raynaud?s Syndrome, and advised that risk outweighed the benefits in regards to receiving the second vaccination in the Moderna Covid-19 series. On 2/3/2021 at approximately 1:45 pm, I received the second Moderna Covid-19 vaccination.  On 2//10/2021, small red, itchy bumps started to appear on both sides of my neck. On 2/15/2021, a bump appeared above my right eyebrow with what felt like a pimple. On 2/21/2021, the pimple had spread towards my inner eye and above my right eyebrow making my right eyelid swell. I received telemedicine care via an e-visit over telehealth with an urgent care and was provided an antibiotic for facial cellulitis. On 2/22/2021, I had one episode of emesis, and went in person to an urgent care. I received a different prescription of an antibiotic, and was provided with instructions of signs and symptoms of what to look for when to report to the emergency room. On 2/25/2021, my right eye started tearing up and the pain began to intensify. I was seen in an outpatient Ophthalmology Clinic and diagnosed with herpes zoster ophthalmicus and postherpetic trigeminal neuralgia. I was placed on a leave of absence from work as of 2/26/2021. 3/1/2021, I was seen in-person appointment with my primary care provider hoping to provide a work note, further assessment of shingles that have spread over neck and back of neck. Primary Care Provider noted diminished bilateral lower extremity muscle weakness and absent deep tendon reflexes. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient received her vaccine with 2 family members in the room who also got the vaccine. Moments after (less than 2 minutes) giving her the vaccine, I was giving another family member the injection and patient asked if she could take her mask off. I turned around and she was very pale. She took her mask off and started slumping in her seat. She was taking deep breaths and reported no difficulties breathing. She then became ill and began gagging, at which point I gave her the trash receptacle to vomit in. I had a technician grab the patient a water and packet of crackers. After half an hour of resting in the chair, monitoring her breathing, blood pressure, heart rate, and getting some food and water into her system, she appeared and reported to feel back to normal. Patient's family member mentioned she had a similar reaction a few weeks ago when getting blood drawn at her doctor's office.
LAB_DATA: Blood pressure was monitored every 5 minutes after initial reaction occurred. Initially, blood pressure was 118/100. At the time patient left roughly 30 minutes after reaction had occurred, blood pressure had stabilized to a range of 115-125/80-90.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Suffered skin lesions in breast and chest and severe ear pain and was diagnosed with shingles and post herpetic neuralgia; Suffered skin lesions in breast and chest and severe ear pain and was diagnosed with shingles and post herpetic neuralgia; This initial spontaneous report was received from a lawyer regarding a case in litigation and refers to a female patient of unknown age. No information was provided regarding medical history, concurrent conditions, or concomitant medications. In or around 03-NOV-2009, the patient was vaccinated (inoculated) with zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) (lot#, expiration date, dose, dose# and route not specified) for routine health maintenance and for its intended purpose: the prevention of shingles (prophylaxis). Shortly after receiving zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) the patient suffered skin lesions in breast and chest and severe ear pain and was diagnosed with shingles and post herpetic neuralgia. As a direct and proximate result of the patient's use of the vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) vaccine, the patient had resulted in physical limitations do not present prior to using the product. Also, experienced mental and emotional distress due to resulting physical limitations and seriousness condition. As a result of the manufacture, marketing, advertising, promotion, distribution and sale of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient sustained severe and permanent personal injuries. Further, as a tragic consequence, the patient suffered serious, progressive, permanent, and incurable injuries, as well as significant conscious pain and suffering, mental anguish, emotional distress, loss of enjoyment of life, physical impairment, and injury. As a direct and proximate results of defendant's conduct, the patient suffered and incurred damages, including medical expenses; the loss of accumulation; and other economic and non-economic damages. The outcome of the event s was reported as not recovered. Therefore, the causality for the event was related to zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX).  The lawyer considered the shingles and post herpetic neuralgia to be disability events.
