Additional details were provided as follows: This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of Recurrent Guillain-Barre Syndrome (GBS), in a male patient of unspecified age, who was vaccinated with Unspecified Influenza vaccine (manufacturer unknown) for prophylaxis.   No information on patient medical or family history or concurrent condition or concomitant medication was reported.  On an unknown date, the patient received Unspecified Influenza vaccine (administration site or route unspecified, dose not reported, batch number not provided). The age at vaccination was not reported.  On an unknown date in 2015, an unknown period after vaccination, the patient was diagnosed with GBS. The patient required 18 days of mechanical ventilation for GBS following influenza vaccination. At that time, the patient was treated with intravenous immunoglobulin (IVIG) and plasma exchange (PLEX) and made full recovery. The patient was eventually discharged to a long term acute care hospital.  On an unspecified date in 2020, the patient received Unspecified Influenza vaccine (administration site or route unspecified, dose not reported, batch number not provided). The age at vaccination was not reported but it could be between 63 years or 64 years at the time of vaccination. On an unknown date, unknown period after vaccination, the patient developed paresthesias of the right hemibody and weakness that progressed to inability to feed himself and ultimately respiratory failure 48 hours later. Approximately five weeks after receiving Influenza vaccine, the patient was admitted to an outside hospital. Magnetic resonance Imaging (MRI) of the neuraxis showed the prior right MCA stroke (Fluid-attenuated inversion recovery (FLAIR) sequence showed the encephalomalacia from the right middle cerebral artery (MCA) infarct). Initial evaluation in the neurosciences intensive care unit found him to be alert. The patient's negative inspiratory pressure (NIF) was -5cm H2O (normal more than 60 cm H2O) and right upper and lower extremity power 0/5 with 0/4 reflexes. The patient was on apixaban for atrial fibrillation; thus, initial lumbar puncture was deferred while waiting for clearance of the medication. Given patient history and examination, PLEX was started. The patient received 5 sessions over a period of 8 days. Lumbar puncture was performed and showed normal cell counts with elevated protein (108 mg/dl (normal 15-45 mg/dl)). Nerve conduction study (NCS) showed prolonged motor distal latencies and severely slowed conduction velocities with reduced compound motor action potential (CMAP). Sural sensory response was normal. F waves were absent. Electromyography (EMG) showed fibrillation potentials (+1) in the right deltoid along with severely decreased recruitment in the right triceps and right tibialis anterior. These diagnostic tests were consistent with GBS and the patient was diagnosed with recurrent GBS. At the age of 64 years, the patient with history remote right middle cerebral artery (MCA) stroke and left hemiplegia was transferred from an outside hospital for ascending weakness of the right hemibody, areflexia, and acute respiratory failure requiring intubation. The patient continued to improve clinically. By day seven, right upper extremity strength had improved to 3+/5 and lower extremity at least 3-/5 in proximal muscle groups. Patellar muscle stretch reflex improved to 1+/4 but Achilles reflex remained 0/4. The patient was successfully extubated and eventually transferred to a long term acute care hospital for anticipated long-term rehabilitation and treatment. The case was considered as serious due to hospitalization. The authors commented "We report a case of recurrent GBS. In both incidences, separated by approximately five years, the influenza vaccine was given within 6 weeks prior to symptom onset. There may be an increased risk for developing GBS from pandemic influenza vaccinations (such as H1N1) compared to seasonal vaccination. Notably, the patient described in our case did not meet all of the characteristics. He was older and had a classic GBS presentation. His presentation, however, was milder than his initial GBS. There likely is a genetic or immunologic host susceptibility that plays a role in recurrent GBS. The Advisory Committee on Immunization Practices currently notes a precaution for revaccination in patients with a history of GBS after an influenza vaccine. The committee also states that influenza vaccination may outweigh the possible risk for certain patients who have a history of GBS within six weeks of influenza vaccine if they are at higher risk for severe complications from influenza. Although recurrence risk is documented to be low, clear risk factors for recurrent GBS have not been consistently defined in the literature. Further studies are needed to determine which patients are at the highest risk for recurrent GBS".  The authors concluded "The risk of GBS following vaccination is low at one to three cases per million patients vaccinated. Additionally, the incidence of GBS recurrence after vaccines appears low but has not been well described. However, despite the low incidence, it is important to carefully weigh risks and benefits of revaccination."

Called PCP, instructed to call Allergist.   At 10:10a call Allergist and the scheduled an appointment for me for 3/9.  At 11:55a wen to ER at hospital.  The injected prednisone, pepcid and Benadryl and did bloodwork.  Throat and tongue began to ease.  Bloodwork results showed increased inflammation and white blood cell count was normal.  Released at 4:45p with prescriptions for prednisone and pepcid for 3 days and instructed to continue with Benadryl.  On 3/9 awoke with same burning symptoms.  Met with Dr. (allergist) and he instructed to continue taking what the hospital prescribed.  He informed for me to get the 2nd vaccine and provided a prescription for Prednisone (5 days) and to be get OTC Pepcid and Zyrtec.  He said to take 2 Zyrtec 2 hours prior to the 2nd vaccine and to take the prednisone and pepcid as needed.  On 3/10 and 3/11 awoke with same symptoms of burning skin.  While taking the Benadryl, the painfulness of stinging/tightness of skin eases slightly, but does not resolve, the skin still burns.  Without the Benadryl, it feels like I will become blistered.

I contacted my primary care physician and he prescribed Methylprednisolone taper and cephalexin antibiotic. I finished my Methylprednisolone taper on a Friday and on that Sunday my rash had now spread to my stomach, underarms, breasts and back. At that point I went to the ER and the PA prescribed a higher dose Prednisone taper and some Triamcinolone cream. Rhabdomyolysis; flu-like symptoms; distress; complaining of severe myalgias in the shoulders and legs; palpitations; dark colored urine; This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of rhabdomyolysis in a 60-year-old female patient who received Herpes zoster (Herpes Zoster vaccine) for prophylaxis.  Concurrent medical conditions included hypertension and thalassemia (minor).   On an unknown date, the patient received Herpes Zoster vaccine. On an unknown date, 1 day after receiving Herpes Zoster vaccine, the patient experienced rhabdomyolysis (serious criteria hospitalization and GSK medically significant), influenza-like symptoms (serious criteria hospitalization), emotional distress (serious criteria hospitalization), myalgia (serious criteria hospitalization), palpitation (serious criteria hospitalization) and urine discoloration (serious criteria hospitalization). On an unknown date, the outcome of the rhabdomyolysis, influenza-like symptoms, emotional distress, myalgia, palpitation and urine discoloration were unknown.   The reporter considered the rhabdomyolysis, influenza-like symptoms, emotional distress, myalgia, palpitation and urine discoloration to be probably related to Herpes Zoster vaccine.  Additional details were provided as follows: This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of Rhabdomyolysis, in a female patient aged 60-year-old, who was vaccinated with unspecified Recombinant Zoster vaccine (manufacturer unknown) for prophylaxis.  The patient had past medical history of hypertension and thalassemia minor. No information on patient family history or concomitant medication was reported.  On an unknown date, the patient received unspecified recombinant zoster vaccination in her left deltoid (administration route unspecified, dosage unknown, batch number not provided), did not have any immediate adverse effects vaccine. The age at vaccination was not reported but it could be between 59 years or 60 years at the time of vaccination.  On an unknown date, next day after vaccination, the patient called reporting flu-like symptoms. Six days after administration, the patient presented in distress, complaining of severe myalgias in the shoulders and legs, palpitations, and dark colored urine. The patient denied dysuria, frequency, urgency, and was afebrile. Urinalysis revealed 3 plus (+) blood and 2+ protein. Laboratory studies showed a creatinine phosphokinase (CPK) level more than 23,000 (iU)/L with significantly elevated aspartate aminotransferase (AST) and alanine aminotransferase (ALT) of 1265 U/L and 747 U/L, respectively. Thyroid stimulating hormone, Lyme disease titers, antinuclear antibody (ANA), rheumatoid factor, viral panel, blood cultures, and further immunologic workup were unremarkable. The patient was admitted to the hospital for severe rhabdomyolysis. The patient denied any previous history of rhabdomyolysis, recent trauma, immobilization, statin use, toxic exposure, and new medications. The patient's symptoms, CPK, and AST/ALT improved over the next several days with aggressive hydration and the patient was discharged in stable condition. At one month follow up, the patient reported complete resolution of myalgias and denied any recurrence of symptoms. The second dose of the recombinant vaccine was not administered. The Naranjo Score was six, characterizing rhabdomyolysis for this patient was a probable adverse reaction. The case was considered as serious due to hospitalization. The authors commented "In this patient, there was no evidence of the common precipitating factors of rhabdomyolysis. While it may be difficult to definitively establish a direct relationship between a specific exposure and an adverse outcome, methods exist to determine its likelihood. Depending upon the cumulative score of 10 questions, a possible adverse reaction is classified as definite, probable, possible, or doubtful. For this patient, positive findings include the following: the adverse event appeared after the drug was given, the adverse event improved after the drug was discontinued, alternative causes were ruled out, and objective evidence of the adverse event was available. These results yield a Naranjo Score of six, characterizing rhabdomyolysis in this case as a probable adverse reaction. Although the exact mechanism of this reaction is not known, we believe an exaggerated immune response to be most likely. The association between rhabdomyolysis and the vaccination is largely based upon the patient's history and exclusion of other common precipitating factors such as trauma or immobilization. Considering the possible lethal complications of rhabdomyolysis and the widespread use of the recombinant zoster vaccine, this potential serious outcome must be acknowledged and symptoms not ignored. Perhaps, patients with a recent history of risk factors such as trauma should delay in being vaccinated. At the least, patients reporting significant myalgias after administration should be tested for rhabdomyolysis".

Co-suspect products included naratriptan hydrochloride (Naratriptan) unknown (batch number UNK, expiry date unknown) for migraine.   Concurrent medical conditions included chronic migraine (sever without aura was taking Naratriptan 2.5 mg).   On an unknown date, the patient received Influenza vaccine and Naratriptan 2.5 mg twice daily (5 mg daily). On an unknown date, 2 weeks after receiving Influenza vaccine and less than a day after starting Naratriptan, the patient experienced myelitis transverse (serious criteria GSK medically significant), urinary retention (serious criteria GSK medically significant), influenza-like symptoms, spinal disorder, numbness in leg, lower extremities weakness of, chest pain, absent reflex, hyperreflexia and overdose. The patient was treated with methylprednisolone. The action taken with Naratriptan was unknown. On an unknown date, the outcome of the myelitis transverse, urinary retention, influenza-like symptoms, spinal disorder, numbness in leg, lower extremities weakness of, chest pain, absent reflex and hyperreflexia were recovered/resolved and the outcome of the overdose was unknown.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the myelitis transverse, urinary retention, influenza-like symptoms, spinal disorder, numbness in leg, lower extremities weakness of, chest pain, absent reflex and hyperreflexia to be related to Influenza vaccine. It was unknown if the reporter considered the myelitis transverse, urinary retention and influenza-like symptoms to be related to Naratriptan. The reporter considered the spinal disorder, numbness in leg, lower extremities weakness of, chest pain, absent reflex and hyperreflexia to be related to Naratriptan.  Additional details were provided as follows: This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of Flu-like symptoms; Naratriptan-Associated Spinal Artery Infarction, in a female patient of unspecified age (in her 40s), who was vaccinated with Unspecified flu vaccine (manufacturer unknown) for prophylaxis.   The patient was in her forties with history of chronic migraine without aura was taking Naratriptan 2.5 mg as needed for her migraines. The patient had no vascular risk factors, medical comorbidities. No information on patient family history or concurrent condition or concomitant medication was reported.  On an unknown date, the patient received unspecified Flu vaccine (administration site or route unspecified, dose not reported, batch number not provided). The age at vaccination was not reported. On an unknown date, 2 weeks after vaccination, the patient presented with flu-like symptoms. On the day of symptom onset, the patient took twice the amount of her prescribed Naratriptan dosage for severe migraine and after 2 hours with still no relief, the patient then took another 2.5 mg. Later that day, the patient developed numbness in her legs followed by severe leg weakness, urinary retention and thoracic chest pain. The patient examination showed flaccid lower extremities and a T4 sensory level with initially absent reflexes, which later became hyper-reflexic. Magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) scans showed T3 to T6 spinal infarction with restricted diffusion on diffusion-weighted imaging and T2 hyperintensity within the anterior spinal artery distribution. Echocardiogram did not show event of patent foramen ovale (PFO). The patient spinal fluid analysis was normal and rest of the neural axis imaging was negative for abnormal lesions. The patient was given 5 days of intravenous (IV) methylprednisolone 1 g daily for the possibility of transverse myelitis with no response. An extensive inflammatory and vascular evaluation, including computed tomography angiogram of the chest and abdomen was negative for dissection, vascular abnormalities, or inflammation. The patient had slow but good recovery and was maintained off tripants and did not have any subsequent neurological attacks over next 4 years. The authors commented "we describe a case of spinal infarction in the setting of naratriptan overuse, an adverse event not previously described in literature".

Patient was asked to wait in parking lot area for monitoring of adverse reaction. At approximately 09:49 a.m monitoring officer called to RN that patient needed assistance.  RN, LPN, EMT-P,   LPN and , LPN went to assess patient at her vehicle. Patient reports "she feels like her throat is tingling, itching, and closing up and just weird." Patient also reported that "she could feel her throat swelling." RN assessed for any rash or swelling and patient only with chest redness but no rash.  RN assessed vitals. BP 138/90, HR 92, Respirations 14. Patient educated on epi injection and possible side effects and patient verbalized understanding. EMS contacted to come assess.  At 09:51 a.m. Epinephrine Injection (Auto Injector) 0.3mg given to right thigh w/o difficulty. Lot# 0FM534, Exp 09/2022.  Patient monitored. Patient stated  at 09:55  "I can already feel my throat getting better and it doesn't seem to be swelling anymore."  EMS arrived at approximately 09:57 to assess patient. Vitals taken by EMT at 10a.m. BP 184/129, HR 88, O2 sat 100%, Respirations 16. EKG performed by EMT . Results were normal.  EMT assessed patients throat and patient continues to report "the swelling and tingling is getting better and I do not feel short of breath." EMT recommended ER visit since epi was administered for eval. Patient declined and states "she feels better and knows what to do if reaction starts again." EMT recommended patient to take Benadryl when she gets home and to go to ER with any additional problems. RN checked vitals again at 1012 a.m. BP 172/120, HR 80, Respirations 16. and asked patient to continue to wait for 20 more minutes for additional monitoring.  Vitals at 1031 a.m BP 168/110, HR 78, Respirations 16. Patient continues to report  "she is feeling much better and ready to go home. Patient left at 10:33 a.m.. Spouse driving. RN contacted patient same day at home at 1353. Patient stated she took 50mg of Benadryl at home and is resting and feeling much better and questioned if she could still get her second dose of moderna vaccine. RN educated she should talk with her Primary Care physician regarding any additional vaccines. Patient verbalized understanding.

Physical Therapy, Steroids or ?   I just want to be able to sleep, be able to dress myself and to wash my hair without pain.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Pain in ankle where they administered cortisone shot and it progressed to bacterial cellulitis infection; Sugar was very high; Blood pressure was very high; Face look flushed; A spontaneous report was received from a consumer concerning a 61-years-old male patient who experienced pain in ankle where they administered cortisone shot and it progressed to bacterial cellulitis infection (cellulitis), sugar was very high (blood glucose increased), blood pressure was very high (blood pressure increased), and face looked flushed (flushing).  The patient's medical history included diabetes mellitus, heart disease (unspecified), kidney failure, and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD). Products known to have been used by the patient, within two weeks prior to the event, included insulin and oral medications for diabetes (unspecified), rosuvastatin calcium, acetylsalicylic acid, umeclidinium bromide and vilanterol trifenatate, diuretics unspecified (water pills), omeprazole magnesium, and cortisone.  On 15 Feb 2021, the patient received their first of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 (Lot number: 038K20A) intramuscularly for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection.    On 17 Feb 2021, the patient got cortisone injection.  On 18 Feb 2021, the patient experienced high sugar level, high blood pressure and face looked flushed.  On 20 Feb 2021, the patient started having pain in the ankle where they administered cortisone shot and it progressed to bacterial cellulitis infection.   Treatment for the events included Keflex.  Action taken with mRNA-1273 in response to the events was unknown.   The outcome of the events of pain in ankle where they administered cortisone shot and it progressed to bacterial cellulitis infection, sugar was very high, blood pressure was very high, and face looked flushed, was considered unknown.; Reporter's Comments: Very limited information regarding the events has been provided at this time.  Further information has been requested.
OTHER_MEDS: INSULIN; CRESTOR; BABY ASPIRIN; ANORO; PRILOSEC [OMEPRAZOLE MAGNESIUM]; CORTISONE
CUR_ILL: COPD; Diabetes mellitus; Heart disease, unspecified; Kidney failure

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Raised, itchy rash at the vaccination site - erupting six days after administration of vaccine.

Janssen COVID-19 Vaccine EUA was administered on Monday March 8th at 4:30pm.  On Tuesday evening of March 9th, I experienced stomach cramping, abdominal paid, and explosive diarrhea. I took an Imodium following this episode. Then on the morning of Tuesday March 10th around 9:30am, I had another round of explosive diarrhea.
LAB_DATA: My symptoms of GI cramping and frequent diarrhea began on December 12th when I seem to have caught some sort of illness or virus from my domestic partner. He came home from work on December 9th with a migraine headache and diarrhea. I experienced these same sets of symptoms starting December 12th, then again on December 21st. The headaches and fatigue stopped, but the diarrhea did not improve for me until February 10th.   On December 29, I had a virtual visit with a doctor to try to identify the source of the GI symptoms. This doctor recommended two types of COVID-19 tests, which both came back negative. I also underwent tests for Giardia Antigen, Ova and Parasites, Fecal Lactoferrin, Rotavirus, Calprotectin, and a Stool Culture as well as comprehensive metabolic panel for bloodwork. All tests came back negative or within a healthy range.   On January 14th, I had a visit with my primary care doctor, for a well woman exam and to discuss the ongoing GI issues/frequent diarrhea. I had changed my entire diet- cutting out dairy, gluten, onions/garlic, alcohol, processed foods, and foods high in sugar, started taking a daily probiotic and women's one a day vitamin and was still not improving.   January 26th: I visited an allergy specialist to test whether the GI issues were related to food allergies. The only test that came back positive was for soybeans- which are not frequently part of my diet.   February 10th, I stopped taking a daily Allegra for environmental allergies and switched to a daily Zyrtec. The GI issues /Diarrhea immediately stopped and I was feeling better for several weeks.  March 8th was when I received the Johnson&Johnson 1 dose, Janssen COVID-19 Vaccine EUA, and the next two days experienced terrible diarrhea one-two times per day.  I contacted my primary care doctor who recommended that I report the adverse symptoms, whether or not they are directly related to the vaccine.  I have experienced a sore arm at the point of injection in my left muscle, but have not noticed any other side effects besides the GI issues.
OTHER_MEDS: Zyrtec and a daily Nature Made, Flonase nasal spray, probiotic 15 billion CFU per serving
CUR_ILL: No known illness at the time of vaccination, but prior to being vaccinated, I had been having gastro intestinal issues with frequent diarrhea in the months of December through mid February. I had gotten better and seemed to be improving when I stopped taking a daily Allegra and switched to Zyrtec.
ALLERGIES: Possibly Allegra Allergic to dog/cat/rodent pet dander and many environmental allergens such as pollen, grass, ragweed
